<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT10-B06-128</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA022-000241-B004-221</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://kragar.eff.org:80/~erict/Scripts/offsite_resources.html 204.253.162.4 19970108040830 text/html 27603
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 04:08:33 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 27431
Last-modified: Tue, 07 Jan 1997 08:53:54 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selena Sol's Public Domain CGI Script Archive and Resource
Library: Offsite Scripting Resources</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = "FFFFFF" TEXT = "000000">

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><IMG SRC = "../Graphics/Scripts/binoculars.jpg" BORDER = "0"></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE=+2>Offsite Scripting Resources</FONT> (<I>Last 
Modified: May 3, 1996)</I></TD> </TR>
</TABLE>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC = "../Graphics/Icons/Lines/smalline.gif"><P></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Note: If you know of other offsite resources, or could provide or add 
to a review of an offsite resource, please send me 
<A HREF = "mailto:selena@eff.org">email</A>.  It is very hard for me to 
keep up with this stuff by myself.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.liveupdate.com/sod.html"
    TARGET = Resource Window">Auto-changing JavaScript MIDI Player</A> - 
    This java script program to play songs continuously, one right after 
    the other as listed.  You can browse all the pages associated to the 
    homepage running this without song interuption, or, you can choose a 
    song to play, iconize the window and the remaining songs will 
    automatically begin after your selection with no further intervention 
    by you or the homepage visitor. 
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.i-depth.com/"
    TARGET = Resource Window">I-Depth</A> - This service allows webites 
    who do not have access to their server like AOL or CIS members run CGIs.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.lakeweb.com/scripts/"
    TARGET = Resource Window">Lake Web's Perl Scripts</A> - Several 
    nicely done and well documented CGI scripts written in Perl including a 
    CGI to send files, one to manage ACESS databases, handle cookies, and a 
    classified add system.
<LI><A HREF = "http://amorn.baremetal.com/netscape/stuff/readme.htm"
    TARGET = Resource Window">Web Search</A> - <A HREF = 
    "mailto:amorn@amorn.baremetal.com">Amorn Chomchoey</A> has created a 
    fantastic meta search engine script which will keyword search multiple 
    search servers (ie Yahoo, Alta Vista, Webcrawler).
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.sdm.de/e/www/hilfe/gen_tree-2.1.tar.gz"
    TARGET = Resource Window">Gen Tree</A> - This Perl script scans the 
    tree (better: the directed graph) of HTML pages of a web site (it's 
    not always a tree because circles and loops are possible!), starting 
    at the home page of that site and following all hyperlinks in a 
    recursive descent (you can also scan just a sub-tree of your web 
    site if you want). Circles and loops are recognized through unique 
    identification of each page by the device and i-node numbers of its 
    corresponding file. When scanning of the web site is complete, an 
    HTML page is generated which contains all the pages found in form of 
    one hyperlink to each of them. The tree structure of the web site is 
    reflected in this page by the indentation of these hyper-links. The 
    text which is displayed in these hyperlinks is extracted
    from the &LT;TITLE&GT; ... &LT;/TITLE&GT; tags inside the corresponding 
    page. The script is capable of executing server side includes and of 
    analyzing server side image maps. This way, no important hyperlinks 
    are missed (many home pages consist of an image map and nothing 
    else!). It is also able to analyze CGI scripts simply by calling them 
    and analyzing their output (therefore, no HTTP server is needed!).  
    Contact <A HREF = "mailto:sb@sdm.de">Steffen Beyer</A> for more info.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.vtt.fi/rte/projects/projects.html" TARGET = 
    Resource Window">VTT Building Technology Project Relational Database</A>
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.virtuflex.com/" TARGET = Resource Window">VirtuFlex
    Software</A> - VirtuFlex provides you with an integrated solution
    to build Internet enterprise applications using Macros instead of CGI 
    scripting. 
<LI><A HREF = "http://w3.gcis.net/~wwd/wcgi/" TARGET =
     Resource Window">WireHead's CGI Scripts</A> - Ken Wronkiewicz has 
     written a couple very useful redirection scripts and offered them as 
     public domain.  even if you aren't interested in the functionality, the 
     code is a nice read anyway.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.rt66.com/proveit/perlscript.html" TARGET =
     Resource Window">Perl Scripts by Sarang Gupta</A> - Sarang has quite 
     a nice collection of webadmin tools for manipulating web related 
     strings and docs.  These scripts are particularly good examples of 
     search and/or replace syntax and because they are short, they are 
     easy to study.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.vex.net/php"  TARGET ="Resource Window">PHP/FI</A>
     - PHP/FI is a server-side html-embedded scripting language. It lets 
     you write simple scripts right in your .HTML files much like JavaScript 
     does, except, unlike JavaScript PHP/FI is not browser-dependant. 
     JavaScript is a client-side html-embedded language while PHP/FI is a 
     server-side language.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.halcyon.com/sanford/cgi/minordomo" TARGET =
     "Resource Window">Minordomo</A> - This is a light weight moderated 
     mailing list.
<LI><A HREF = "http://summer.lh.umist.ac.uk/~deutch/stcount/" TARGET =
     "Resource Window">ST Count</A> - STcount is an easy to install, 
     easy to use access counter (requires SSI) and it's free of course. 
     Nothing fancy, but functional and accurate.  Another great script 
     brought to you by <A HREF = "mailto:vtonic@netor.gr">Spiros Trivizas</A>
     with fast <A HREF = "http://www.netlink.co.uk/~pronet/stcount/">mirror 
     site.</A> 
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.rmnet.it/pnet/cgi/cgistart.htm" TARGET =
     "Resource Window">People Net CGI Discussion Forum</A> - This topic 
     covers discussion of the development of Common Gateway Interface (CGI) 
     scripts as  they relate to Web page authoring. Possible subjects 
     include discussion how to handle the results of forms, how to 
     generate images, and how to put together other interactive Web 
     offerings.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/usamaw/logscribe/" TARGET =
     "Resource Window">LogScribe: Web Access Logging</A> - The script was 
     written to maintain logs and display them in a graphical
     format using an easy menu-driven interface. The script is free and comes
     with no restrictions on its use.
<LI><A HREF = "http://solaris.tryc.on.ca/files/files.phtml" TARGET = 
     "Resource Window">Wojciech Tryc's</A> very coolarcdhive including a 
     good shopping cart and SQL gateways.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.eff.org/cgi-bin/cookie.p">cookie.p</A> and 
    <A HREF = "http://www.eff.org/cgi-bin/expcookie.p">expcookie.p</A> 
    are a couple of scripts written by <A HREf = "mailto:brown@eff.org">Dan 
    Brown</A> which handle the management of Netscape cookies.  The 
    script collection can be downloaded <A HREF =  
    "http://www.eff.org/scripts/cookie.tar">here</A>. 
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.propertyguide.com" TARGET = "Resource
    Window">Jump Button</A> - The scrip for this can be found at <A HREF 
    = "http://www.propertyguide.com/scripts/url.txt" TARGET = "Resource
    Window">http://www.propertyguide.com/scripts/url.txt</A>. Basically 
    the script allows one to jump to any URL in a list from a drop down 
    box.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.boutell.com/tools.html" TARGET = "Resource 
     Window">Thomas Boutell's Web Tools Page</A> - Boutell is one of the 
     true web wizards and this page has invaluable resources especially for 
    the C programmer.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.selah.net/udload/udload.cgi" TARGET =
    Resource Window">Upload.cgi</A> This is a good example of using the 
    new File Upload procedures in a CGI.  Script by <A HREF = 
    "mailto:steveh@pbsi.com">Steve Hsueh</A>.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.jemtek.com.au/jemtek/cgi/lib" TARGET =
    Resource Window">JemTek CGI</A> - JemTek CGI is a C library designed 
    to simplify the creation of dynamic World Wide Web (WWW) 
    applications.  This is a very good, very fast, and well documented C 
    library (like cgi-liib.pl but for C)
<LI><A HREF = "http://math.unr.edu/linguistics/scripts/" TARGET = "Resource
    Window">Kristina's Scripts for Educators</A> - an absolutely 
    brilliant set of scripts for teachers on the web.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.schiele-ct.de/cgi-bin/jhquery/ezforms!entry.sd"
    TARGET = "Resource Window">EZforms</A> - EZforms allows you to 
    install HTML forms on your ISP's server and easily retrieve the data
    entered by visitors in a readable form, without any CGI rights on that 
    server. Instead, the form data is stored by EZforms, until you decide 
    to look at it.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.igs.net/~hooper/smh/products/internet/sendcgi.htm"
    TARGET = "Resource Window">SMH Software's SendCGI</A> - This is a
    modified version of Matt Wright's FormMail script that allows a
    information to be sent to the user by e-mail by simply filling out their
    e-mail address and pressing SUBMIT
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.33online.com/scripts/" TARGET =
    "Resource Window">Jason Berry's Perl Scripts</A> - Includes a Polling 
    Script and a SSI Footer script.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.virtualville.com/library/cgi.html" TARGET =
    "Resource Window">Introduction to the Common Gateway Interface (CGI)</A>
    - A very nice beginners and intermediates guide to CGI.

<LI><A HREF = "http://summer.lh.umist.ac.uk/~deutch/ststat/ststat.html" TARGET = 
    "Resource Window">STstat</A> - STstat is a set of CGI scripts that 
    produce statistics  based on the various logs that the Http server keeps.
     It displays the remote hosts that have accessed the server
     it's running on, as well as the most popular URLs of that
     server.  here is a faster <A HREF = "http://www.netlink.co.uk/~pronet/ststat/">mirror site</A>

<LI><A HREF = "http://www.webcom.se/projects/freeware/" TARGET = "Resource
     Window">WebCom's Freeware CG Scripts</A> - Very nicely presented 
     freeware page with a few well written NT/C++ CGI's (File uploading, 
     file listing, guestbook, and URL redrtection)
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.virtualcenter.com/scripts2" TARGET = "Resource
     Window">The Scripts Homepage</A> - a very nicely presented script 
     archive that has most of the scripts that you might want (free for 
     non-commercial uses).
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.nmt.edu/~bsittler/projects.html" TARGET = "Resource
     Window">Benjamin Sittler's Scripts</A> - a few CGI's without much 
     documentation or examples, but fun to read anyways.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.hkstar.com/~west/perl/" TARGET = "Resource
     Window">West Raymond's Script Archive</A> - a nice little archive 
     with some well written and useful scripts for web site maintenance 
     (including a nice link tracker to see which links on your web site are 
     bad)
<LI><A HREF = "http://web.syr.edu/~jlhollin/bib.html" TARGET = "Resource
     Window">BiblioBasket</A> - a simple, free-ware, perl script which 
     enables an interactive sorting of bibliographic citations on the 
     web. It sorts incoming citations by relevant section, and also saves 
     each citation to a separate flat-file in "BASIC" text format. 
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.olen.com/baby" TARGET = "Resource 
     Window">Interactive Pregnancy Calendar</A> - The Interactive 
     Pregnancy Calendar will build a day-by-day customized calendar 
     detailing the development of a baby from before conception to birth.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.netamorphix.com/cgi.html" TARGET = "Resource 
    Window">Netamorphix CGI 
    Resource Page</A> - a fantastic site for basic information on CGI's 
    as well as detailed and encompassing lists (Unlike most CGI resource 
    lists, Netamoprphix provides well-described list 
    elements - short abstracts of each and every script on a monthly 
    rotation) of shareware/freeare CGI scripts.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.netlink.co.uk/users/PureAmiga/pcgi/index.html" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">Pure CGI Scripts</A> - A very good list of 
    links to freeware scripts recommended by Pure Web.  Most of these I 
    have here, but not all of them...
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.ocii.com/~bsowa/scripts.html" TARGET = 
    "Resource Window">The Zone Coasters Scripts</A> - A small, but well 
    written script archive containing an excellent survey script, a 
    guestbook, a bbs, a chat, and homepage maker that were particularly 
    interesting to me.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.perl.hip.com/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Perl for 
    Win32</A> - A pretty good 
    web developers kit for CGI implementation on NT.
<LI><A HREF = "http://kufacts.cc.ukans.edu/info/forms/forms-intro.html" 
     TARGET = "Resource Window">Web
     Masters</A> - The ultimate reference page outlining the mechanics 
     behind CGI-HTML form interaction.  An easy read for those of you 
     interested in the nuts and bolts
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.shareware.com/" TARGET = "Resource 
    Window">Shareware.com</A> - You can 
    grab pretty much any shareware around for NT, Mac or UNIX web 
    servers including Perl, Gzip, Tar.  Each of these are a good addition to 
    any cgi support library, and since all of my scripts are gzipped, 
    tarred, and written in Perl, each are pretty essential for using the 
    scripts in this archive!
<LI><A HREF = "ftp://june.cs.washington.edu/pub/ntemacs/utilities/" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">Decompression 
    utilities for NT</A> - an excellent ftp archive to download gunzip and 
    tar for NT's so that you can grab the compressed archives of my scripts.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.virtualville.com/library/scripts.html" TARGET 
    = "Resource Window">CGI 
    Scripts To Go</A> - A good collection of various CGI scripts by topic 
    (17 topics in all).  The maintainer has taken a good deal of time to 
    describe each script and compare it to other similar ones in the 
    topic.

<LI><A HREF = "http://www.cs.wustl.edu/~seth/txt2html/" TARGET = 
    "Resource Window">Seth Golub's Text 
    2 HTML</A> Perl Converter - a little bit complicated to use, but 
    extremely powerful if you have a lot of conversion to do.
<LI><A HREF = "http://kufacts.cc.ukans.edu/info/forms/forms-intro.html" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">An 
    Instantaneous Introduction to CGI Scripts and HTML Forms</A> - an 
    excellent page for the basics.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.microlink.net/~gentle/Demo/" TARGET = 
    "Resource Window">Rod
    Elis' Script Archive</A> - an excellent archive with examples of form 
    processing, search engine, message board, HTML-CGI interface to 
    build HTML pages on  the fly, shopping carts, authentication.
<LI><A HREF = "http://amadeus.ccs.queensu.ca/cgihacks/hacks.html" TARGET 
    = "Resource Window">The
    Hitch-Hackers Guide CGI Toolkit</A>
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.comvista.com/net/www/cgi.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Jon Weiderspan's
    CGI Applications Directory</A> An Excellent Launchpad!  Jon has put 
    togther a fantastic "list of links" for just about any CGI you want 
    (both public domain listings as well as commercial listings).
<LI><A HREF="http://www.engr.iupui.edu/~dbewley/perl/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Dale Bewley's
    Public Domain Tools Site</A> contains a motley of excellent tools for 
    the web administrator (especially graphics tools).
<LI><A HREF = "http://freenet.msp.mn.us/people/drwool/webconf.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">David
    Woolley's</A> list of BBS conferencing systems...EXCELLENT list of links.
<LI><A HREF = "http://zippy.sonoma.edu/~kendrick/nbs/unix/www" TARGET = "Resource Window">New 
    Breed's</A> Software Page. (Inlcudes SSI, cgi libraries, index 
    creator, leave_link.cgi, Guestbook, Counter)
<LI><A HREF="Source/homepage_generator.tar" TARGET = "Resource Window">Automatic Homepage
    Generator</A> - a tar file put together by <A HREF = 
    "mailto:cl@txcc.net">cl@txcc.net</A>.  It is a page
    that makes general home pages The idea is that a ISP can offer it to
    there users so that even the newest Net person can make a home page.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.worldwidemart.com/scripts/" TARGET = "_top">Matt 
    Wright's Script Archive</A> - What can I say, Matt's Script Archive 
    is one of the best out there and he is only 13!!!
<LI><A HREF="http://bakmes.colorado.edu/~bicanic/altindex.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Nick
    Bicanic's Animation Page</A> - This is a really good site from which 
    to learn animation.  Nick taught me everything I know on the subject...
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.techware.com/eva">Eva CGI Development Language
    Site</A> - I don't know too much about the language, but the site 
    looks pretty swank.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.delta-design.com/parsely.html" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">Kerry Garrison's Search and Replace</A> - Parsely is 
    a small perl script written by Kerry Garrison that goes through a 
    list of text files and does a text replacement.  A very important 
    tool for any webadmin with a large site to manage.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.dnaco.net/~aleed/scripts.html" TARGET = "Resource 
     Window">Andrea
     Leed's</A> Archive.  (Last time I checked, scripts included a 
     groupware Calendar and Browser matcher which will tell you which 
     browser you are using).
<LI><A HREF="http://bakmes.colorado.edu/~bicanic/cindyanim.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Cindy</A>
    (only here as an example of the animation script!)
<LI><A HREF="http://member.aol.com/royalef/gifmake.htm" TARGET = "Resource Window">Royal
    Frazier's</A> Absolutely Amazing Animation Tutorial on CGI Animation
<LI><A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/people/nathan/netnoose/" 
    TARGET = "_top">Hangman</A> - Yep, you got it...your basic CGI 
    version of Hangman...
<LI><A HREF="http://www.maxinfo.com/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Max-Info WebC</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/CGI___Common_Gateway_Interface/" TARGET = "_top">Yahoo CGI Resources</A>
    No surprises here, just a quick link over to Yahoo.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.semcor.com/~muquit/Count.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Access Counter (Count 2.2)</A>
    - This is the standard access counter for UNIX and NT.  Written in C, 
    the script is not "too" hard to install and has been recently expanded 
    with lots of new features.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.communitycu.org/OnlineServ/Calculators/C2.html" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">Calculation Scrips</A> - you can click on any 
    of the Financial Wizard(TM) calculators to get instant online 
    assistance in determining optimum loan payments, maximum mortgage 
    affordability or even your personal retirement income strategy.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/alweiner/cgi-bin/homepage.cgi?w3magic" 
    TARGET = "Resource Window">W3Magic</A> - W3MAGIC is a tool that adds
    over 100 new high-level tags to all your HTML documents.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.vv.com/~stanley/cos.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Netsville Scripting Services</A>
    - (shareware shopping cart, "live type" - chat stuff, database search 
    engine, PDN article search) 
<LI><A HREF="http://bio.bu.edu/WebEvent/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Web Event</A> - 
    WebEvent is an interactive online calendar program which allows 
    individuals or groups to share event (calendar) information via the 
    World Wide Web. WebEvent runs on UNIX platforms using PERL and a flat 
    database. 
<LI><A HREF="http://www.eit.com/goodies/software/" TARGET = "Resource Window">EIT 
    Software Archive</A> - A bunch of pretty cool webadmin tools
<LI><A HREF="http://glimpse.cs.arizona.edu:1994/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Glimpse</A> a web-based 
    Search Engine
<LI><A HREF="http://www.wiwi.uni-frankfurt.de/~deinzer/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Eric Deinzer's 
    Break Dancer Animation</A> - pretty self-explanatory...just a cool 
    CGI animation.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.selah.net/cgi.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">The 
    CGI Collection</A> - A well described selected listing of various CGI 
    resources recommended by Robert Niles such as Mailform, W3OClock, 
    Guestbook, PickMail, Logger, Access Counter,  and Register.

<LI><A HREF="http://www.best.com/~hedlund/cgi-faq/" TARGET = "Resource Window">A CGI 
    Programmer's Reference</A>Hedlund's CGI FAQ.  These pages are 
    intended to collect information useful to Common Gateway Interface (CGI)
    programmers. 
<LI><A HREF="http://www.stars.com/Vlib/Providers/CGI.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Web
     Developer's Virtual Library</A> - Lots and lots of CGI links.  And 
     excellent resource for the C CGI programmer, and even a couple of NT 
     links.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.middlebury.edu/~otisg/Scripts/index.shtml" TARGET = "Resource Window">Otis'
     CGI Library</A> A really good collection of CGI's (multimailer, 
     lottery, log analyzers, animation) 
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cbil.vcu.edu:8080/cgi-bin/cgis.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Chris
     Stephens' Shareware CGI's</A> - One of the stand out features of 
    this archive is its coverage of the rare AppleScript and VMS CGIs!

<LI><A HREF="http://arpp1.carleton.ca/grant/mac/cgi/random.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Grant
     Neufold's Random URL Shareware CGI</A> - Random URL is a CGI 
     application for WebSTAR or MacHTTP (or any other CGI sdoc compatible
     web server) which randomly returns an url, from a text file, to clients.
<LI><A HREF="http://ute.usi.utah.edu/bin/cgi-programming/counter.pl/cgi-programming/index.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Intro
    to CGI Programming at the University of Utah</A> - This document 
    contains an introductory tutorial on CGI programming, including some 
    example CGI programs. After completing this tutorial you will be 
     able to develop your own CGI programs.
<LI><A HREF="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/docs/cgi/overview.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">NCSA's
     The CGI Page</A> - Not much to say beyond the title.  This is an 
     excellent overview of CGI from the Godfathers of the Web.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.abo.fi/~csundqvi/cgi.htm" TARGET = "Resource Window">Christoffer "Toffe"
     Sundqvist's Web Developers Bookmarks</A> - A fairly good list of links.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.seds.org/~smiley/cgiperl/cgi.htm" TARGET = "Resource Window">Mooncrow's CGI/PERL
     Source Page</A> - A fantastic list of links that no CGIer shouold miss.
<LI><A HREF = "http://mendel.hgp.med.umich.edu:80/doc/unix/tasks.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">UNIX
     Command Quick Reference Page</A> - Jeff Aspinall's fantastic 
     overview of some of the more frequently needed UNIX commands 
<LI><A HREF = "http://website.ora.com/software/" TARGET = "Resource Window">O'Reilley's WebSite 
     Software Library</A> - If you are an NT CGI Programmer, this is a must 
     have for your bookmarks.  This is about the best NT resource I have 
     seen.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.atmos.washington.edu/perl/perl.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Perl 
     Programmer's Handbook</A> - This is a fairly good resource for the 
     experienced Perl Hacker.  A little bit too technical for my taste, but 
     anything by Larry Wall is great.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www1.cis.ufl.edu/perl/ TARGET = "Resource Window"">University of Florida's Perl
     Page</A>.  This is an excellent launchpad if you are looking for more 
     info on Perl.  Good links to perl libraries too.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.eecs.nwu.edu/perl/perl.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">The Perl Reference
     Materials Page</A> - An absolutely fantastic page covering Perl 4 
     and 5 with links to pretty much everything a budding Perl hacker would 
     need to take her deep into the world of Perl.  I would make sure to 
     have a good four or five gours if you dare stop here. 
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.illuminatus.com/cookie" TARGET = "Resource Window">Andy Kingston's Netscape 
     HTTP Cookie Notes</A> - This is an excellent toutorial on using the 
     magic cookie.
<LI><A HREF="http://www-genome.wi.mit.edu/WWW/examples/Ch9/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Lincoln D.
     Stein's CGI Examples</A> - Examples from Lincoln Stein's fabulous 
    book on wevb server administration.  I recommend buying the book itself, 
    but in the meantime, you can read through the example scripts.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cyserv.com/pttong/cgi.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Dave 
     Elis' CGI Page</A> - Another resource for the non-UNIX CGI 
    programmer.  Dave's site includes links to AppleScript, Windows, and 
    Visual Basic information
<LI><A HREF="http://www.adams1.com/pub/russadam/hukisoft.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">Russ
    Adam's Excellent Perl Search Engine</A> - Hukilau Search Engine is 
    pretty nice. It is fairly similar to my own search engine, but not 
    enough that you want to not read trhough how Russs does it.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.alma.com/" TARGET = "Resource Window">Excerpt Search
    Engine</A> - I have not tried this search engine out myself, but it 
    looks pretty nice.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.physnet.uni-hamburg.de/provos/talk/" TARGET = "Resource Window">N-Talk Chat
    Script</A> - A cute interface to N-Talk for all of you with a UNIX 
    web server.
<LI><A HREF = "http://wintermute.ncsa.uiuc.edu:8080/map-tutorial/image-maps.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">The
    Image Map Tutorial Page</A> - An incredible tutorial, I would not 
    miss it if you are interested in making imagemaps for your site.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.halcyon.com/davidg/imagemap.html" TARGET = "Resource Window">David
    Geller's Guide to Imagemaps</A> - Anotehr fantastic imagemap reference
<LI><A HREF = "http://skpc10.rdg.ac.uk/gb/gl4nt.htm" TARGET = "Resource
    Window">Guestlinks4NT</A> - Guestlinks4NT is a combined guestbook and 
    URL submission script for Windows NT servers.
<LI><A HREF = "http://skpc10.rdg.ac.uk/misc/randomcounter.sht" TARGET = 
    "Resource Window">RandomCounter</A> - RandomCounter provides the perfect 
    alternative to all those neat odometers - a short Perl script
    that introduces a customisable random number onto your page wherever you 
    want (uses SSI's). 
 </UL>

