<HEAD><TITLE>Index of /pub/Net_info/Guidebooks/Hytelnet/Unix</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<H1>Index of /pub/Net_info/Guidebooks/Hytelnet/Unix</H1>
<PRE><IMG SRC="/icons/blank.xbm" ALT="     "> Name                   Last modified     Size  Description
<HR>
<IMG SRC="/icons/back.xbm" ALT="[DIR]"> <A HREF="/pub/Net_info/Guidebooks/Hytelnet/">Parent Directory</A>       17-Oct-96 12:00      -  
<IMG SRC="/icons/unknown.xbm" ALT="[   ]"> <A HREF="hytelnet.tar.gz">hytelnet.tar.gz</A>        25-Jan-94 09:21    44k  
</PRE><HR>
<PRE>
[You will need to get InfoZip's unzip utility. It can be found at ftp.eff.org,
pub/Net_info/Tools/unzip_vms.exe (see also the README.unzip_VMS in that 
directory) for the VMS version.  For the Unix version, get unzip50.tar.gz, 
in the same directory.]

	    About the Hytelnet Software  - July 6, 1993
	    ===========================

The Hytelnet software (version 3) consists of the following files:

    FILENAME       DESCRIPTION                       PLATFORM
                                                     Unix  VMS
    README.FIRST   This file                           x    x
    Changes	   List of changes in the software     x    x
    Makefile	   Makefile for hytelnet               x
    make.com	   Command file to make hytelnet            x
    hytelnet.c	   Hytelnet source code                x    x
    vmscompat.c	   VMS-specific routines                    x
    hyindex.c	   Simple indexing program             x
    hyindex.com	   Simple indexing program                  x
    hytelnet.1	   Documentation (Unix man page)       x
    hytelnet.doc   Documentation (plain text)               x
    index	   Index (used by the 'i' command)     x    x
    help	   Hytelnet help screen                x    x
    read.me	   Some info on hytelnet               x    x
    start	   The 'Welcome to Hytelnet' screen    x    x
    whatis	   Still more info on Hytelnet         x    x

Note:

    In order to use the Unix or VMS versions of Hytelnet you must have
    the PC version.  The PC version is available via anonymous ftp from
    ftp.usask.ca (128.233.3.11) in the /hytelnet/pc directory.

    If you do not already have an unzip utility for Unix, you can get
    unzip50.tar.Z from the ../hytelnet/unix directory on ftp.usask.ca.

    If you do not already have an unzip utility for VMS, you can get
    unzip50.exe from the ../hytelnet/vms directory on ftp.usask.ca.
 

To make and install the Unix version:

    First install the files from the PC version of Hytelnet on your
    Unix host.  For example: 

    % cd /usr/local/hytelnet
    % unzip hyteln65.zip	(extract readnow and hytelnet.zip)
    % unzip -a hytelnet.zip	(extract the rest)
    % rm *.zip *.exe help.txt read.me start.txt whatis

    Then install the Unix Hytelnet files:

    % gunzip hytelnet.tar.gz
    % tar -xvf hytelnet.tar
    % make hytelnet

    The help, read.me, start, whatis and index files from this archive
    should be placed in the same directory as the unziped PC Hytelnet
    files.


To make and install the VMS version:
 
    First install the files from the PC version of Hytelnet on your
    VMS host.  Then make Hytelnet.  For example:
 
    $ set default pub:[hytelnet]
    $ unzip hyteln65.zip        (extract readnow and hytelnet.zip)
    $ unzip -a hytelnet.zip     (extract the rest)
    $ del *.zip.,*.exe.,help.txt.,read.me.,start.txt.,whatis..
 
    Then copy the VMS Hytelnet files into this directory and make the
    VMS version of Hytelnet:
 
    $ copy ...
    $ @make      (use "@make multinet" if you use Multinet)
 
    The help, read.me, start, whatis and index files from the VMS version
    should be placed in the same directory as the unziped PC Hytelnet
    files.
 
    Note: for the benefit of VMS users who do not have a C compiler,
          I have placed two pre-compiled versions of hytelnet
	  in the vms directory.  These are: hytelnet.exe and
	  hytelnet-multinet.exe.

Telnet, tn3270, rlogin, finger, ftp, pad

    The Unix and VMS versions of Hytelnet notice these commands
    embedded in the database, and will execute them for the user,
    if desired.


Configuration

    If you install the Hytelnet data files somewhere other than in
    /usr/local/hytelnet (pub:[hytelnet] on VMS), you will have to
    change the definition of STARTDIR in hytelnet.c.

    You can disable the execution of external commands by running
    Hytelnet with the -secure option.  Or you can edit the makefile and
    define SECURE before compiling the program.

    On VMS systems, external command execution is automatically disabled
    for anonymous users (those who login under the name 'hytelnet').

    On Unix systems, it is disabled for anonymous users from outside
    the local domain.  For this to work, edit hytelnet.c and define
    DOMAIN_CUE to be a unique substring of your domain (eg. ".usask.ca").

    To allow anonymous users to telnet-out, edit hytelnet.c and change
    the definition of ANONYMOUS_USER to "".

    A few sites require that a port number be specified in the
    telnet command.  The syntax for this varies on VMS and DOS systems.
    If this doesn't work for you, you may have to play around with the
    definition of PORTSEP in hytelnet.c.


Please let me know if you have any problems with the Unix or VMS
versions of Hytelnet.

Earl Fogel
-------------------------------------------------------------------
earl.fogel@usask.ca		Computing Services, Room 56 Physics
Phone: (306) 966-4861		University of Saskatchewan
Fax:   (306) 966-4938		Saskatoon, Sask. CANADA, S7N 0W0
</PRE>
</BODY>
</DOC>
